<p class="note"><strong>Quick answer:</strong> A proper VPN speed test checks download, upload, latency and jitter under comparable conditions. Modern protocols (WireGuard family) and nearby servers deliver 80–90% of your original speed.</p>

<h2>What does a VPN speed test measure?</h2>
<p>It’s not just about one “number”. Speed tests reflect how efficiently your VPN handles data transfers and network latency. Key metrics include:</p>
<ul>
 <li><strong>Download speed</strong> — how fast data reaches you; affects streaming and downloads.</li>
 <li><strong>Upload speed</strong> — how fast you send data; important for calls and backups.</li>
 <li><strong>Ping (latency)</strong> — round-trip time in milliseconds; lower is better for gaming and VoIP.</li>
 <li><strong>Jitter</strong> — latency variation; spikes cause lag or audio glitches.</li>
 <li><strong>Packet loss</strong> — missing packets that force retransmission and slow apps.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to test VPN speed accurately</h2>
<ol>
 <li>Start with a baseline (no VPN) using a trusted speed test service.</li>
 <li>Connect to the nearest VPN server and repeat the test 3 times; average results.</li>
 <li>Switch to a mid-distance server (e.g., another state or region) and test again.</li>
 <li>Compare download, upload, and ping values to identify where speed drops.</li>
 <li>Try different protocols (WireGuard, IKEv2, OpenVPN) to see which performs best on your network.</li>
 <li>Record results at different times of day to factor in ISP congestion.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Reading your results</h2>
<p>If you get 80–90% of baseline speed on nearby servers, your VPN is well-optimized. Drops below 60% mean it’s time to change server location or protocol. Higher latency (100 ms+) is fine for streaming but hurts gaming and calls.</p>

<h2>Practical ways to make your VPN faster</h2>
<ol>
 <li>Use WireGuard or NordLynx instead of OpenVPN.</li>
 <li>Connect to the closest server physically and logically.</li>
 <li>Choose a different city within the same region to avoid crowded servers.</li>
 <li>Use Ethernet or strong 5 GHz Wi-Fi instead of 2.4 GHz.</li>
 <li>Close background apps syncing data (cloud, game updates).</li>
 <li>Restart router to clear bufferbloat and improve latency.</li>
 <li>Try Split Tunneling to exclude non-essential apps (<a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-split-tunneling.html">learn more</a>).</li>
 <li>Use servers tagged as Streaming or P2P for those tasks (<a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-server-types.html">server types explained</a>).</li>
 <li>Run a DNS leak test to ensure resolvers aren’t slowing down (<a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-dns-leak.html">DNS leak guide</a>).</li>
 <li>Keep your VPN app updated — new versions often boost speed.</li>
</ol>

