<h2>Common testing mistakes</h2>
<ul>
 <li>Comparing different targets for baseline and VPN tests.</li>
 <li>Testing only once instead of multiple runs.</li>
 <li>Using Wi-Fi during rush hours — use Ethernet when possible.</li>
 <li>Ignoring upload and jitter values.</li>
 <li>Sticking to slow protocols like OpenVPN-TCP by default.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Advanced diagnostics: when results look “wrong”</h2>
<p>Sometimes your numbers look inconsistent across runs. Before blaming the VPN, check for background sync (cloud drives, system updates), QoS rules on your router, and overloaded test targets. Try two independent testers and keep the one that’s closer to your real-world apps (streaming vs. large file mirrors). If Ethernet outperforms Wi-Fi by a lot, interference or 2.4 GHz congestion is the likely culprit.</p>

<h2>Streaming, gaming and remote work scenarios</h2>
<h3>Streaming</h3>
<p>Throughput matters most. Aim for stable download above 25–50 Mbps for 4K streams with reasonable headroom. Specialized locations often work better; see our <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-streaming.html">VPN for streaming</a> guide and, for specific services, <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-netflix.html">Netflix</a> or <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-bbc-iplayer.html">BBC iPlayer</a>.</p>

<h3>Gaming</h3>
<p>Latency and jitter dominate. Pick a server closest to the game region. If ping still spikes, switch protocol (WireGuard → IKEv2) and move from Wi-Fi to Ethernet. Our <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-for-gaming.html">gaming guide</a> covers hitboxes, tick-rate, and NAT quirks.</p>

<h3>Remote work & calls</h3>
<p>Video calls need consistent upload and low jitter. Test at the same time you usually meet. If your corporate stack uses split DNS or strict firewalls, match the VPN protocol to your network (often IKEv2). See <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-remote-work.html">remote work</a> and <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-banking-online.html">online banking</a> for stability tips.</p>

<h2>Protocol impact on speed</h2>
<p>In 2025, WireGuard-based stacks typically win on raw throughput and CPU efficiency, while OpenVPN-TCP remains the slow, compatibility fallback. OpenVPN-UDP can be fine on stable networks; IKEv2 shines on mobile because it roams between networks quickly. Compare options in our overview: <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-protocols.html">VPN protocols</a>.</p>

<h2>Server choice: proximity vs. capacity</h2>
<p>Nearby servers aren’t always fastest. Capacity, peering and congestion matter. If your closest city underperforms, try another in the same region, then a neighboring country. For task-specific performance use tags like Streaming or P2P; details in <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-server-types.html">VPN server types</a>.</p>

<h2>Mobile testing specifics</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Use airplane mode toggle before each run to clear radio state.</li>
  <li>Prefer 5 GHz Wi-Fi; on LTE/5G, cell load varies minute to minute.</li>
  <li>Disable battery savers that throttle background networking.</li>
  <li>On iOS/Android, try protocol auto → WireGuard → IKEv2; keep screenshots of each run.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Suspecting ISP throttling?</h2>
<p>If your baseline to certain video CDNs is consistently worse than the same path over VPN, your ISP may shape traffic. Compare against <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-geo-blocks.html">geo-blocked services</a> and run tests to multiple targets. A well-peered VPN can restore normal speed, but expect a small latency trade-off.</p>

<h2>Security settings that also influence speed</h2>
<p>MTU mismatches, DNS timeouts, and aggressive kill-switch rules can hurt performance. Start with defaults from your provider, then fine-tune using our <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-optimal-settings.html">optimal settings</a> checklist. Always re-test after each change.</p>

