<h2>Quick troubleshooting checklist</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Retest on Ethernet → compare to Wi-Fi.</li>
  <li>Switch server (same region → neighbor city).</li>
  <li>Change protocol (WireGuard ⇄ IKEv2 ⇄ OpenVPN-UDP).</li>
  <li>Restart router; avoid 2.4 GHz; close heavy background apps.</li>
  <li>Exclude non-critical apps via <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-split-tunneling.html">Split Tunneling</a>.</li>
  <li>Verify no <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-dns-leak.html">DNS leaks</a> or packet loss.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="faq">FAQ — VPN speed testing</h2>
<div class="faq">
  <details><summary>How many runs do I need for reliable results?</summary><p>Three runs per location and protocol is a good balance. Average the numbers and repeat at a different time of day to account for congestion.</p></details>
  <details><summary>Which tester should I use?</summary><p>Use any reputable service, but keep it consistent across baseline and VPN runs. Also try a second site to cross-check anomalies.</p></details>
  <details><summary>Why is upload fine but download slow?</summary><p>This often indicates server congestion or suboptimal peering. Change city or protocol; check for background downloads on your device.</p></details>
  <details><summary>Will a dedicated IP make my VPN faster?</summary><p>Not inherently. It can improve stability on corporate networks but speed depends on capacity and routing. Learn more: <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-dedicated-ip.html">Dedicated IP</a>.</p></details>
  <details><summary>My ping is high only in games — what now?</summary><p>Connect to a server near the game’s region and use UDP-based protocols. If Wi-Fi spikes persist, switch to Ethernet.</p></details>
</div>

